Because we will be making payments monthly, we will divide the annual rate of 17.5% by 12 to get the monthly rate.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.175}{12}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{1.46\%}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the rate we'll use in our first calculation is 1.46%.

First, again convert the 8.9% annual rate to a monthly rate by dividing it by 12.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Rate} &=\dfrac{0.089}{12}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{1.46\%}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the monthly rate for the new credit card is 0.74%.

Let's now determine how fast we can pay the loan in the new card compared to the old card.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{TS on the NC} &= \text{144}-\text{80}
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\text{\bf64 months}}
\end{aligned}$$

**Based on our calculations, we can pay off the loan balance 64 months faster on the new credit card than we can on the present card.**

Finally, determine how fast it will take us to settle the loan on the new card with a 2% charge compared to the present card.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{TS on the NC} &= \text{144}-\text{82}
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\text{\bf62 months}}
\end{aligned}$$

**Assume the new card charges 2% on transferred balances; we'll still be able to pay off the loan 62 months faster than with the current card.**
